{"/service/ndnp/rp/batch_rp_froghemoth_ver01/data/sn91070631/00516991677/1908041501/0101.xml":{"full_text":"Uniitg frifame.\nPROTTDWNCfI. R. L\nPUBLICATION OFFICE*\n1M.144 WENTMINNTBMB STREET.\nFREDERIC N. LUTHER.\nwrrrofi\nTHATCHER T. THURSTON.\nAssort att editor.\nP\u00bbR MONTH. Me. PCT TBAX\nSINOUE COPIES ONTC CENT.\n\u2022ncLEFnoKFz-T'Nio\u2019* w.\nPrivate Breach Oanectina with\nAH Derartmerta\nErtarM M \u2022waM-Ote\u2019V Mail Metter July 4.\nIBOA \u00abt the Feat Office at PmvUenca. R u\nunde- the Act ot Conrr\u00bb\u00bb\u00ab of March A 1878\nAH Derartmenta\nEntereS aa l***M-\u00bbu Mai! Matter July 4.\nIBOA at the Feat Office at Prevalence. R U\nunde* the Act of Conareee of March A lal\u00df\nUnsolicited manuscripts art submitted\nat the sender's risk of loss.\nReturn postage should accompany all\ncommunications to the Editor to tihtch\nt reply is desired.\nThe Editor cannot make himself re\nef -sible for such matter, although he\nwill endeavor to return whatever is\nc- \u2019\u2019able for publication provided the\nnecessary postage is enclosed.\nAnonym f >ns er \u2022sanitations will re\nceive no consideration whatever.\nWEDNESDAY, APRIL IJ, 1908.\nTHE AVERAGE DAILY\nCIRCULATION OF\nCbe morning tribune\nFOR THE MONTH OF\nMARCH\nWAS\n11,507\nCorio\nMr. O\u2019Cannell*w Law.\nRepresentative John F. O\u2019Connell of\nthis city has good reason to be pleased\nwith the passage of his bill for the es\ntablishment of a free employment bu\nreau. With a commendable desire to\nlie of service to his constituents in a\npractical way he has taken an intelli\ngent and active interest in this sub\nject from the first, and it is largely\nthrough his unremitting attention to it\nand his earnest efforts that we are now\nto enter upon an experiment that may\nlead to very valuable results. Massa\nchusetts has found a similar experi\nment worth continuing and enlarging,\nand conditions are not essentially dif\nferent here. Of course it is desirable\nthat we should equip ourselves with\nevery practical means of solving the\nproblem of the unemployed.\nFrom Politico to Banking,\nThe announcement of Senator Rath\nbone Gardner that with the expiration of\nhis present service in the General As\nsembly his political career must for the\npresent cease relieves the Democratic\nparty of a certain embarrassment.\nWhile it was generally thought that he\nwas in a way entitled to that party\u2019s\nnomination for the governorship it was\nnot clear how he could very well be\nplaced at the head of the State ticket\nin a presidential year when he had him\nself declared his intention to support\nthe Republican national ticket. His pol\nitics is not of a kin*! to suit either party\nentirely, but his personal character and\nhis professional and business ability\ncommand the respect of all; and as\nPresident of the Union Trust Company,\nto the duties of which position he very\nproperly purposes to devote his entire\ntime, he will have opportunity to render\nthe public a greater service than he ever\nhas rendered or perhaps ever could\nrender in political office.\nPresident and House at Odds.\nAs was predicted in the House a few\ndays ago, President Roosevelt has re\nturned without his approval a bill which\ncontinues the life of a franchise grant\ning valuable water privileges for the\npayment of which no provision is made.\nWhat disposition will b\u00bb made of the\nmeasure by the committee on inter\nstate and foreign commerce to which\nit has been referred is problematical, of\ncourse, but the feeling is apparently very\nstrong in Congress against any further\nextension of the Government's jurisdic\ntion where State rights are concerned.\nAt the same time, there is something to\nlx* said, surely, in favor of safeguard\ning the interests of the public, and the\nhistory of legislation for many years\nmakes it clear that States and cities as\nwell have neglected their duty in this\nr<\u00abpect. Whether the abuse is so fla\ngrant, however, as to demand the in\nterference of the Federal Government is\na question that has not yet been de\ntermined.\nBelated tefegwarda.\nGovernor Hughes of New York\nsigned on Monday a number of bank\ning reform bills which confer upon the\nSuperintendent of the State Banking\nDepartment authority to investigate the\ncharacter and fitness of all persons de\nairing to incorporate a new bank and to\nuse his discretion in dealing with their\napplication*; which place certain re-\nMraints upon investments by trust com\npanies and which proside for the com\nputation of the value of securitie*. It\nis less surpriung. surely, to learn that\ntlresr elementary mra\u00abure\u00ab have met\nnith the approval of legislators than it\nh to reflect that X\u2019ra York ha< been\nwithout them all the-c years. But it\nwould appear that there, as elsewhere,\nthere has been inexcusable laxity re\ngarding the supervision and control or\nregulation by State authorities of bank\nIng institutions, private or other, and in\nthe circumstances it is fortunate that\nthere has not been more dishonesty and\nthat the indifference noted has not re\nsulted in heavier losses.\nThia Will Nat Oat\nThe bill w hich the committee on spe\ncial legislation reported to the House\nyesterday in amendment of the law for\nthe suppression of intemperance is a\nsorry answer to the popular demand in\nthis State for increased restrictions on\nthe liquor traffic. In effect, indeed, it\nis a refusal; for it contains not one pro\nvision that would materially alter the\nconditions under which the manufac\nture and sale of intoxicating liquors are\nnow carried on. It is a miserable pre\ntence of reform which can deceive no\nbody and which discredits not the in\ntelligence so much as the honesty of its\nsponsors.\nWhile, as The Tribune pointed out\nyesterday, it may not be feasible to pro\nscribe all saloons within a fixed distance\nof all schools and churches, an attempt\nto do so is ridiculously inadequate\nwhich makes the distance only two hun\ndred feet and applies it to only public\nschools, not to parochial schools and\nchurches. And while the real need now\nis for a closer regulation of the sale\nof liquor on any day of the year rather\nthan an increase of the number of days\non which it is forbidden, it is certainly\nsenseless to provide for the closing of\nsaloons on Labor Day and Christmas\nand not on other holidays. Such con\ncessions as these are really no conces\nsions at all; they are but a mockery of\nthe temperance sentiment of the com\nmunity.\nThere can be no substantial improve\nment in the liquor license legislation of\nthis State which does not begin with a\nlimitation of the number of licenses in\nproportion to population. And rather\nthan pass a law which does not provide\nfor such limitation the General As\nsembly, and the Republican party which\nis in responsible control, might better\nrefrain from action altogether and so, in\neffect, declare openly and honorably that\nthey do not care or do not dare to com\nply with the popular desire for closer\nrestriction of the liquor business.\nThat there is such a desire at the\npresent time is so apparent to every\nthoughtful and observant citizen that it\ncannot he wholly unknown to even the\n\u201csmart\" politicians. It has not sought to\nimpress itself through lobbyists and paid\nattorneys, and it is not shown at its\nstrongest in petitions and in temperance\norganizations. Rut it exists in every\ncorner of the State, in every grade of\nsociety, and it is increasingly in earnest.\nFrom the lowest point of view, there\nfore, it is unwise for any party to as\nsume responsibility for such contemptu\nous trifling with it as is the bill re\nported to the House yesterday.\nThe miserable measure will not do,\nand the Republican members of the As\nsembly should see clearly that it will not\ndo. It is not fair to the people of the\nState; it is not safe for the party. For\nthe most \u201cpractical\" machine managers\nmust know that in the long run\u2014and\nnot such a very long run, either\u2014the\napproval of the great mass of the sober\nand thoughtful pcdple of the community\nis worth far more than the tainted sup\nport of the liquor dealers in cither votes\nor money.\nCollege Denomlaatioaaliom.\nRather curiously, it would seem, it has\nl\u00bbecn left to one of \"the cloth\" recently\nto discover that the number of Congre\ngational ministers on the board of fel\nlows of the Yale corporation is entirely\ntoo large. He would have Episcopa\nlians and the Catholic Church repre\nsented. to the end that the university\nmentioned may be broad and inclusive\nin all such matters.\nThis subject has received attention\nbefore, of course, but of late years not\nmuch has been heard concerning de\nnominationalism with reference to our\nhigher institutions of learning, and pub\nlic and preparatory schools are not\noverburdened, surely, by religious in\nstruction of any kind. As a matter of\nfact, with a few notable exceptions, it\nmay be doubted if the average parent or\nstudent is acquainted with the denomi\nnational complexion or leaning of the\ncolleges of this country. Their output\nis no longer intended, as formerly,\nalmost exclusively for professional life\u2014\nthe pulpit or bench or bar\u2014and while\nmore or Jess religious influence may\nstill be exerted by them it is of a gen\neral character and, whatever the home\ntraining or preferences, it is improbable\nthat any young man would find himself\nout of sympathy with the doctrine\npreached, provided he could be induced\nto listen to it. For the most part, it\nseeks to be all-embracing and extremely\ntolerant, so tolerant, indeed, that those\nwhn are brought within its range barely\nrealire that it has even a slight hold\non them.\nNevertheless, if it is urged, as it\nsometimes is, that, apart from denomi\nnational ism, the composition of college\nboards should he governed largely by\nfinancial and business considerations it\nmight be reasr|iably concluded that\nthere is no place in it for clergymen;\nand outside of educational circles, at\nleast, there is a suapicion that the mod\nern trend is in the direction of their ex\nclusion because the modem trend is in\ntensely practical, which the writer of\nsermons usually is not. The latter :s\napt to be visionary and rather indiffer-\nTHE MORNING TRIBUNE. PROVIDENCE, R. 1.. WEDNESDAY. APRIL 15. 1908.\nent to purely material success. More\nthan that, he ia without the means\nwhich enables him to contribute to en\ndowments, to found chairs, establish\nscholarships or build costly and ornate\nbuildings.\nWhat seems to be wanted in the na\nture of uplifting impulses is not clerical\nideals but counting room methods. In\nvite the opulent merchant and the\nlordly banker to the stewardship of the\ncolleges and interest them in the work\nand its necessities. On special occa\nsions, for a trifle, it will be possible to\nsecure the services of the parson to offer\nprayer.\nA Coming Maa.\nThe most interesting figure in the\nBritish Cabinet as reorganized under the\npremiership of Mr. Asquith is Mr.\nLloyd-George, the new Chancellor of\nthe Exchequer\u2014more interesting, even,\nthan Mr. Churchill, though that dashing\nand audacious young man always fills\nthe eye fetching!?. The former is un\nquestionably a coming man in British\npolitics; in considerable degree, indeed,\nhe must be said to have already arrived.\nFew have ever risen as rapidly as he\nto full Cabinet position: and. though\nopportunity has had some part in his\nadvance, his exceptional ability in tak\ning advantage thereof must be allowed\ndue credit.\nWhile he made his first impres\nsion, when in opposition, as a tire\nless, eloquent and aggressive agitator,\nthe brilliant administrative qualities\nwhich he displayed but lately as Presi\ndent of the Board of Trade have\nstamped him also as a man of unusual\npower on the constructive side. These\nsame qualities will of course stand him\nin good stead in the higher and more\nresponsible office which he now as\nsumes and, provided he does not de\nvelop the traits of Joseph Chamberlain\nwhich are now faintly to be observed in\nhis make-up. he has a combination of\nequipment which may carry him very\nfar indeed. At this moment, at least,\nhe is certainly the foremost leader of\nthe young Liberalism of the day.\nA New \u201cI nele Tom\u2019* Cabin.**\nNew York dramatic critics apparently\nagree that a brand-new \u201cUncle Tom\u2019s\nCabin\" w hich has been produced in their\ncity and which deals with political\nethics will not prevail.\nSmall wonder! There is no room,\nand there has never been room in\n\u201cUncle Tom\u2019s Cabin\u201d for political\nethics or anything else, for that matter,\nthat Mrs. Stowe did not put into it with\nher own entertaining pen. All the\nspace is fully occupied, from the floors\nof the Southern mansion and the negro\nquarters to the cracked ice in the Ohio\nRiver and the stearft-heated cotton field;\nand on the stage it is still more crowded\nbecause Eva and Topsy and the blood\nhounds and Uncle Tom and Legree and\nEliza and the rest have doubled up, so\nto speak, and are taking their meals at\nthe same table. Furthermore, and what\nis certainly far more important, they are\n\u201ctaking\" with delighted, spellbound au\ndiences and have been, 10, these many\nyears. Where ethics, political or other,\nis concerned, it is enough to know,\nsurely, that in \u201cUncle Tom\u2019s Cabin\u201d\nRight triumphs and Wrong is shown\nto the door, although it must be\u00bbadmit\nted that there are thrilling moments\nwhen it looks rather hazy for Right.\nHowever, we want no new \u201cUncle\nTom\u2019s Cabin;\u201d the original stage ver\nsion is all-sufficient and entirely satis\nfactory in every respect, from the open\ning dialogue between Uncle Tom and\nGeorge Harris to the pathetic though\npainless death of Little Eva. We have\nhoped and prayed, perhaps, that Little\nEva might be spared, at least for one\nmore act. but it was not to be and the\nintroduction of political ethics cannot\nprolong her life. Her malady, it will\u2019\nbe recalled, was consumption.\nBut. in any event, the slightest inter\npolation or omission would be imme\ndiately noted and resented\u2014< blood\nhound more or less or an extra potted\npalm. We insist, every one of us, and have\nalways insisted, that \u201cUncle Tom\u2019s\nCabin\" shall remain as it has been, char\nacters, setting, properties, motive, ren\ndition and moral, forever and a day and\neven longer if it be so willed. Wc want\nour children and our children\u2019s children\nthrough countless generations t> sec\n\"Uncle Tom\u2019s Cabin\" as we saw it: we\ntrust that we may talk it over with them\nin heaven and learn what they think\nof it.\nA new stage version of \u201cUncle l orn\u2019s\nCabin\u2019 As well talk about a new stage\nversion of Rip Van Winkle.\u201d\n\u201cI am glad,\u201d says Mr. John D. Rocke\nfeller, \u201cto be able to say that I love\neach and every one of my fellow-men.\nIt is a great thing to be able to say\nthat truthfully.\" It is indeed, and a\ngreater to have proved it.\nIt is correct, of course, to say that\nthe fleet is \u2018'home again,\" now\u2019 that it\nhas dropped its anchors in the territorial\nwaters of the United States; and the\nexpression forcibly reminds us how big\na place \u201chome\" is.\n1 o many, no doubt, it will seem re\ngrettable that the affair of President\nCastro cannot be settled by the admin\nistration of a good swift kick, without\nany of the refinements of diplomacy.\nIt\u2019s a pretty slow corporation lawyer\nwho cannot by this tune name preciselv\nthe points wherein the new Employers\u2019\nLiability law will be declared invalid by\nthe Supreme Court.\nThere's a difference between dinners\nand prestige Npringfleld Republican.\nAnd, judging from the attitnde of\ncertain foreign potentates toward our\ndiplomats, it is in favor of the dinners.\nWhatever racing may have done for\nhorses, it doesn\u2019t seem to have un\nproved the breed of certain legislators.\nCommenting approvingly op Presi\ndent Roosevelt\u2019s treatment of tlfi negro,\nthe New York Age saj* that \u201cattention\nshould be called to the class of men he\nhas appointed to office.\u201d It might at\nleast serve to divert the attention of a\nweary public from the class of men\nhe has removed from the Army.\nRecent convention proceedings in sev\neral States seem to warrant the some\nwhat surprising assumption that certain\nDemocrats are enjoying a lucid interval.\nCharity being what it is, it is not im\nprobable that the reduction noted in the\nnumber of unemployed who apply for\nfood is due to the quality of the food.\nPerhaps, after all, the conference at\nThe Hague did bring something to pass.\nTake, for example, the case of the\nUnited States and Venezuela.\nCucullus non facit monachum; neither\ndoes one of those hats make a merry\nwidow, though it may possibly in some\ncases make a widow merry.\nThe proposition to call out the State\nmilitia to suppress race-track betting in\nNew- York suggests that some remedies\nare worse than the disease.\nIf there is anything the colored\nbrother can think of that he wants it is\nclear that this is the time for him to\na\u00abk for it.\nGovernor Ma goon seems disposed to\nprepare Cuba for self-government hy\nremoving most of her provincial Gov\nernors.\nChehca w\u2019ould appear to have a first\nclass opportunity to refute a venerable\nsuperstition bearing on its lack of en\nergy.\nU hen Senator Crane\u2019s hack is turned\nthe Massachusetts delegation may be\nsaid to be tentatively for Secretary\nTaft.\nEvery other week or so Mr. Bryan\nmakes the amazing discovery that free\nsilver is no longer an issue.\nGovernor Johnson\u2019s backwardness and\nindifference must be utterly Incompre\nhensible to Mr. Bryan.\nOne could perhaps endure spring\nbetter if it came only once a year.\nMOST IMPORTANT IfISVB.\nTime and Work Will Noire the Prob.\nlemi of Life.\n'From the Wall Street JdhrnaJ.)\nSense My that there can be no return of\nprosperity until Roosevelt Is retired te\nprivate life. Others say that there can\nbe no return of prosperity until the\nStandard Oil pays that twenty-nine mil\nlion dollar fine and Harriman and Ryan\nare deposed from financial power.\nSome say that there can be na revival of\nprosperity until Congress, with its two\nhundred and fifty bills to regulate the\nrailroads, adjoin-ns. Others say that re\nvival depends upon a physical valuation\nof the railroads, made with a view to\nlower freight rates.\nSome say that the future of the country\ndepends upon putting rich malefactors in\nJail, while others declare that it wilt go\nto ruin unless the Anarchists are deported\nand the Socialists suppressed.\nSome say that the nation will be in\nvolved in moral wreck unless the stock\nexchange is closed up, while others just\nas insistently declare that there will be\nan industrial collapse unless the doctrine\nof the closed shop is overthrown.\nSome say that ths most important prob\nlem before the people Is the revision of\nthe tariff, while others nay that all other\nproblems fade into insignificance beside\nthat of the prohibition of the liquor traf\nfic.\ngome declare that national safety de\npends on the maintenance of the right of\nprivate property and the inviolability of\ncontract. While others hold that there can\nbe no hope for the future until there is a\nmore equal distribution of wealth.\nA complete list of \u201cthe most Impor\ntant issues before the country\u201d would ftll\nan entire issue of the Wall Street Jour\nnal. and it Is constantly growing. It is\nbarely possible that the time may soon\narrive when the people will get tired of\nproblems and. sweeping \"the meet im\nl\u00bbortant issues\u201d into the dust pan and\nthence into the ash heap, will simply go\nto work. Time and work are the greatest\nsolvers of problems in the world.\nAspa r agus has made its appearance and\nthe season for certain shellfish and\ngreen corn is approaching, all of which\nsuggests that some of the moat highly\nprited delicacies are extremely difficult\nIn the eating, so to speak. To fully en\njoy them it Is necessary to do away with\nknives, forks and spoons and depend\nupon the hand*. No utensil, whether of\nseasoned wood or I* a ten gold or pure\nsilver, has been devised which does not\ninjuriously affect their flavor.\nHomo there are, fastidious fol\u00df,\nuse a fork on asparagus, but their over\nrefinement robs them of much of the\npleasure that that luxury should afford.\nIt is true that a limp, spineless aspara\ngus stalk, dripping with melted butter or\na Krench dressing or a white paste, is\nfull of perplexities. To eat it properly\none must imitate young birds In the nest\nand there Is no mother bird to steer tt\ndown one's threat and away from one s\ntap or waistcoat. Htlll, It Is possible to\nlift and get under It, and, while prac\ntice In this ease never makes perfect. It\ngenerally helps the contortionist a little.\nThen there is green corn; green corn off\nthe cob Is of no earthly use. It is advisa\nble to take both hands to green com, and\nto attack It rather savagely, as If tt were\nan unconquered and almost unconquer\nable article of diet. CUnu, too, belong\nlh the same category, and lobsters at\ntheir best, fresh from a bake, hot and\ntasting of seaweed, onions, clams,\nchicken, fish, dressing and the like,\nshould be pul I*4 apart with the fingers.\nAppearances may be against shore din\nner customs or manners, but appearances\nare often deceptive.\nl\u00aba\u00bbt summer a small boy from the\nFar West stood and wide*\nNAVY** PTNCM BOWLS.\nWhn t\u00ae Ow\u00ab Tb\u00aen* After the War\nteip* Ceaaa to Bet\n(From th* Tacoma L*dser.)\nOn the baltleehlpa and cruleere of the\nUnited State* are silver services *nd\nother gift* of an estimated value of 12W.-\nOHO, yet the title to this property does not\nrest in the Government or anybody else.\nSecretary Metcalf of the Navy ask* Con\ngress to enact a law placing title in the\nFederal Government so that in the event\nthefts are committed the Government\nmay punish the offender. It Is a timely\nsuggestion. After a while the battleships\nand cruisers will be worn out. They will\nwear out a great deal sooner than the all- t\nver services, What, then, will become of\nthe gifts made by States and cities? Will,\nthey be held by the Governrnent and\nturned over to new battleships or new\ncruisers bearing the same name as the\nvessels worn out? These are questions\nfor Congress to decide.\nThe States and cities after which naval\nvessels have been named have made their\ngifts without giving special thought to\ntitle. The intention has been, no doubt,\nthat the gifts shall be the property of\nthe Government for use on the ships. Sec\nretary Metcalf finds that the title rests\nnowhere. Congress should consider, too,\nwhether the silver services and other\ngifts shall remain the property of the\nGovernment, after the battleship or\ncruiser has cessed to be, or whether they\nshall be returned to the States and cities\nthat presented them. In the course of\nfifty years, if the custom of presenting\ngifts continues, the Government might\noome into possession of more silver ser\nvices than could be used en vessels In\nthe Navy. Silver services might pile up\nlike Junk at the national capital.\nSpeeding Penalties Abraad.\n(Fr\u00abm the Daily Consular Reports.)\nConsul General H. H. Ridgely of Bar\ncelona reports that laws against reckless\nautomobiiing are becoming more severo\nand specific in Europe, lie cites the\nfollowing;\n\u201cIn France a law has just been enacted\nwhich punishes with heavy fine and sev\neral months Imprisonment any conductor\nor owner of an automobile who, having\ncaused any sort of an accident, or who,\nhaving been in a collision with any other\nvehicle yr Individual or object, does not\nimmediately stop and give his name and\naddress to the police or to other repre\nsentatives of the law'. Tilts punishment\nIs to be specifically imposed, quite Irre\nspective of the merits of the case itself.\nThus, the offender would be liable for\ndouble punishment) first, for not having\nstoppod to give hls name and address, and\nsecond, for having caused the accident.\nOn the other hand, he might be held\nguiltless of wrong in the matter of the\naccident itself, but he would nona tie\nleas certainly be punished in the first\ninstance. In short, the purpose of the\nqew French law, which will In all .Iknli\nhood be Immediately enacted by all other\nContinental countries, is to separately\nand specifically punish the chauffeur\nwho, having been In an accident, runs\naway without disclosing his identity,\nTalk Abowt Inflation!\n(From the Rprinirfleld Republican.)\nNow and then a national bank presi\ndent Is found who favors the Aldrioli\nCurrency bill. One such, the president\nof a bank in Washington, appeared be\nfore the House banking committee yes\nterday and urged that the bill be changed\nback again to admit railroad bonds ai\nsecurity and then further changed to al\nlow the issue of one billion dollars of\nemergency notes instead of the five hun\ndred million dollars or so permitted to\u201d\nthe bill as it stands. Talk about Infla\ntion! This bank president would shame\ntho wildest of Populists, When Chair\nman Fowler asked him where he would\nget, the gold to form a redemption reserve\nfor such an issue of notes he called it a\n\u201ccatch question\u201d and refused to answer.\nBut an answer was not needed. He plain\nly didn't know.\nSigne of Retnrntng Confidence.\n(From th* New York Mail.)\nA young woman who boarded a north\nbound Broadway local at Nin\u00abty-slxth\nstreet at 12:26 yesterday afternoon wore a\nbrown hat' thirty-four inches In diameter\nand 3.1416 times that in circumference. It\nhad been oaid for.\nToe Frank.\nFrom Judge.)\nThere wan a young lady named Kent,\nWho always said Just Vhat the meant.\nPeople said, \"Hhe\u2019s sincere;\nBhe speaks without, fear\"\u2014\nBut they shunned her by common con\nsent.\nTaft and Haghee.\n(From the Atlanta Constitution.)\nTaft and Hughes; it\u2019s a good ticket.\nIt is difficult to s\u00bb*e h\u00abw tne Republi\ncan party could better it.\neyed in the doorway of a clamheuoe.\nLance, perspiring men and flushed women\nwith napkins tucked under their chins\nwere working frantically with their\nhands on clams, green corn, lobsters and\nbrown bread. There was the contented,\nsteady crunch that Is heard In the cow\nbarn when the cattle are feeding.\n\"Mother,\u201d said the small boy. pointing\nat the busy people bending over the\ntables, \u2019\u2018what are those?\u201d\nsee\nWhere the Kansas City Times got its\nInformation Is a mystery, but it says\nthat for a recruit the most annoying\nthing In navy life Is the absence of aide\npockets in uniform trousers. It Is easy\nto believe It and It is surprising that\nthere are any roerults. The average man\nwould a* soon think of going without\ntrousers as of going without side pockets.\nFashion once decreed that evening trous\ners or dross pants, as they arc some\ntimes called should have no side pockets\nand \u2019\u2022society\u201d promptly disbanded for\nthe winter. At a party a man eail't\nthink of much to nay even when he ean\nthrust hla hands in his pockets and weave\nhack and forth and when there are no\npockets he is speechless; he can't an\nswer a simple, civil Attention. He wants\npockets all over him and soose men has o\nthem drilled Into their bathing suit*.\nAnd It is singular that no pocket la\never ao full, though all sorts of things\nmay be protruding from It, that there\nisn't room la II for a hand. It wl)| be\nrecalled that years and year* ago eur\nmo\u2019herq occasionally threatened to \"sew\nup\u201d our pockets and \u2019hat we Immediately\nthrew a series of reform fits and he\nhated ourselves for the bettor part of a\nforenoon,\nt. t, r.\nCI